Detecting and fixing data skew.

Data skew is when a few keys dominate the partition distribution. And because a stage cannot complete until its very last task finishes, a single oversized partition stalls the entire stage.

So what are the symptoms? One task runs ten to a hundred times longer than the median — you can see this in the Spark U-I, under stages. One executor shows garbage-collector pressure, or disk spill, while all the others sit idle. And the stage finishes quickly, except for the last one or two tasks.

There are three fixes, and here they are in order of preference.

First, the A-Q-E skew join. This is the modern default — Spark three point two and later ship with skew-join enabled. A-Q-E detects the skewed partitions at runtime, and splits them. Try this first.

Second, salting. You manually break up the hot keys — you append a random suffix to the join key on the large side, and you explode the small side n times to match. This is the most reliable fix, when A-Q-E is not enough.

And third, repartition-by-range. You sort by the column, and split into equal-sized ranges, so the partitions are balanced regardless of key frequency.

And note — the same disease shows up in group-by. Same medicine. Salt the key, and aggregate twice — a partial aggregate, then a final one.
